dataObjects.subject: http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/SPMInfoItems#GeneralDescription
dataObjects.title: Biology
dataObjects.description: Inhabit lakes and large rivers (Ref. 4967).  Occur in shallow water with muddy bottom.  Omnivore, feed on plankton, mollusks, seeds and detritus (Ref. 13868).  Oviparous (Ref. 205).  Nested eggs are guarded by the male parent (Ref. 47642).  Furthermore,  the male plays host to eggs and young of Dinotopterus cunningtoni which takes advantage of the already prepared nest and feed on the host brood (Ref. 49546). An example of interspecific brood care.

dataObjects.subject: http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/SPMInfoItems#Distribution
dataObjects.description: Africa:  present in most rivers of West Africa, Lake Chad, the entire Congo River system, the Nile, East African lakes, and the rivers Omo and Giuba.
dataObjects.references: Risch, L.M. 1986 Bagridae. p. 2-35. In J. Daget, J.-P. Gosse and D.F.E. Thys van den Audenaerde (eds.) Check-list of the freshwater fishes of Africa (CLOFFA). ISNB, Brussels; MRAC, Tervuren; and ORSTOM, Paris. Vol. 2. (Ref. 3236)

dataObjects.subject: http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/SPMInfoItems#Morphology
dataObjects.description: Dorsal spines (total): 1; Dorsal soft rays (total): 7 - 8; Anal spines: 3 - 4; Analsoft rays: 7 - 8
dataObjects.references: Brichard, P. 1978 Fishes of Lake Tanganyika. T.F.H. Publications, Inc., Neptune City, New Jersey. (Ref. 681)

dataObjects.subject: http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/SPMInfoItems#DiagnosticDescription
dataObjects.description: Head large with heavily built body (Ref. 4967).  Marbled or spotted gray, with a few black spots arranged in rows.
dataObjects.references: Brichard, P. 1978 Fishes of Lake Tanganyika. T.F.H. Publications, Inc., Neptune City, New Jersey. (Ref. 681)

dataObjects.subject: http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/SPMInfoItems#Migration
dataObjects.description: Potamodromous. Migrating within streams, migratory in rivers, e.g. Saliminus, Moxostoma, Labeo.  Migrations should be cyclical and predictable and cover more than 100 km.

dataObjects.subject: http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/SPMInfoItems#LifeCycle
dataObjects.description: Eggs are brooded and guarded by the male parent (Ref. 47642).
